{{Quote|I think it's the Corbet dictum: 'What is, is without'|[[Deak Starkiller]] to [[Kane Starkiller]]|<ref name="The Star Wars: Rough Draft">[[The Star Wars rough draft|''The Star Wars'' rough draft]]</ref>}}
The '''Corbet dictum''' was a saying that [[Kane Starkiller]] had his sons memorize as part of their [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] training. It was the answer to a conundrum posed by the [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]] with a cube that [[Deak Starkiller]] had been examining.

Deak's precociousness with Jedi doctrine outstripped his brothers', but he died shortly thereafter at the hands of a [[Unidentified Knight of the Sith|Knight of the Sith]].

==Behind the scenes==
In the first draft, Deak is renamed [[Deak Starkiller|Bink Valor]] and his father, [[Kane Starkiller|Akira Valor]]. They have exactly the same lines. When Deak reappears as an [[Aquillian Ranger/Legends|Aquillian Ranger]] in the [[Adventures of the Starkiller, Episode I: The Star Wars|second draft]], he is older and already trained as a [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]], and the scene has been eliminated.

This phrase resembles one of the precepts of Master [[Yoda/Legends|Yoda]]: ''"No! Try not. Do, or do not. There is no try"'', in [[Star Wars: Episode V The Empire Strikes Back|Episode V]], mostly through its syntax and inversion of expectations. It is, however, obscure in its meaning without much surrounding context.

